===Etymology 1===
Attested in the {{l|ja|日本書紀|tr=''Nihon Shoki''}}, completed in 720 and one of the earliest works written in Japanese (see [[Wikipedia:Nihon Shoki]]), with a meaning of {{{term|lang=en|bed}}.

According to the {{Jpan|和句解}} (''Wakuge''), published in 1668 by early Edo-period scholar Matsunaga Teitoku ({{Jpan|松永貞徳}}; see [[Wikipedia:ja:松永貞徳]]), derives from ゆか (''yuka'') as the {{term|lang=ja|未然形|tr=''[[mizenkei]]''||[[irrealis]] form}} stem of the verb {{term|lang=ja|行く|tr=yuku||to go}} of an original meaning similar to "not going", in reference to a place where one sits down to rest.

====Noun====
{{ja-noun|k|hira=ゆか|rom=yuka}}

# The [[floor]] (the bottom surface of a room).
# A [[bed]].
# {{context|theater|lang=ja|sort=ゆか}} A raised area of a [[stage]] where a [[presenter]] or [[musician]] sits.
# A raised [[platform]] erected along the Kamo River in Kyōto in summer, used as an outdoor [[tea]] shop or [[restaurant]].

