===Etymology 2===
Shared origin with {{l|ja|所}} ({{l|ja|ところ}}, ''tokoro''), "place".  Attested since at least the Nara period, appearing in the {{l|ja|万葉集|tr=''Man'yōshū''}}, completed in 759 (see [[Wikipedia:Man'yōshū]]).

====Noun====
{{ja-noun|k|hira=とこ|rom=toko}}

# A [[raised]] [[platform]] roughly 30cm tall used in dirt-floored rooms as a [[seat]].
# A raised area on which to sleep: a [[bed]].
# The [[floor]].
# [[tatami|Tatami]] mats.
# The seat of an [[oxcart]].
# Short for {{l|ja|床間}} / {{l|ja|床の間|tr=''toko no ma''}}: An [[alcove]] with a raised floor along one wall of a traditional Japanese living room.
# An alcove with a raised floor used as a [[study]]: see {{l|ja|付書院|tr=''tsukeshoin''}}.
# A [[box seat]], such as at a [[parade]], [[theater]], or [[stadium]].
# Short for {{l|ja|床店|tr=''tokomise''}}: A [[stall]] with a raised floor used as a store.
# Short for {{l|ja|床屋|tr=''tokoya''}}: A [[barbershop]], from how such shops were historically often ''tokomise''.
# Short for {{l|ja|床船梁|tr=''tokofunabari''}}, {{l|ja|舵床|tr=''kajidoko''}}: The large [[wooden]] [[beam]] at the very [[aft]] of a traditional [[wood]]-[[hulled]] Japanese [[ship]], upon which the [[rudder]] is seated.
# The [[heel]] of a [[plough]]; the part of the bottom of a plough that touches the ground and guides the [[ploughshare]].
# Short for {{l|ja|苗床|tr=''naedoko''}}: A [[seedbed]].
# Short for {{l|ja|鉄床}}, {{l|ja|金床|tr=''kanatoko''}}: An [[anvil]].

